Added support for a simpler charting API.

What's new:

1) Support for builder-style chaining of method calls in Charts.
Example:
  (Chart(df, 'line_chart').x_axis().y_axis()...ETC...)

2) Top-level chart builders for all chart types.
Example:
  LineChart(df)

These builders use sane defaults for each chart type, although I only
implemented defaults for LineChart so far.

Use dataframe index as the x axis in charts.

In the process, I also unified DEFAULT_COMPONENTS and
REQUIRED_COMPONENTS in charts. This simplifies things, even though the
end result is slighly less customizeable charts. For instance, now every line
chart will have the x_axis component set, and there's no way to unset
that.

For now, this should be more than good. But we need to think about how
much customizability we want for the future.

How to use.
* build everything
* `make local` - copies local/client/build to `/tmp/streamlit_local` for now
* start up a webserver ie `cd /tmp/streamlit_local; python2 -m SimpleHTTPServer 8080`
  or `cd /tmp/streamlit_local; python3 -m http.server 8080`
* Run an example `python examples/mnist-cnn.py`
* Click on the save icon. (this will pop open up a new window with the links)
* Kill proxy.
* Click on links now.  you might have to shift refresh.  I need to figure out the websocket logic.

Start using a more pythonic setuptools setup.py

This is probably the only real good documentation and best practice on the mess that is setup.py and i will be referencing it.
[https://blog.ionelmc.ro/presentations/packaging/#slide:1](https://blog.ionelmc.ro/presentations/packaging/#slide:1)

* Move everything in dist which should be a transient directory into the root level directory.
  * setup.cfg isn't needed as setup.py can include the README.md directly ie `python3.6/site-packages/streamlit-0.8.1-py3.6.egg/EGG-INFO/PKG-INFO` see https://blog.ionelmc.ro/presentations/packaging/#slide:8
  * Move toplevel README.md to CONTRIBUTING.md because its more for developers.
    * Add a section on how to use MANIFEST.in because data_files,
      package_data arent really what people use. see [this](https://blog.ionelmc.ro/presentations/packaging/#slide:15) and [this](https://blog.ionelmc.ro/presentations/packaging/#slide:16)
    * Move README.md to top level.
* Use pip-compile to manage requirements
  * Move requirements.txt to requirements.in  This will be the file in
    the future you want to edit when adding new dependencies.
  * requirements.txt will have version control so we know what versions
    work and if we have to pin something to a specific version, it can
    happen in requirements.in
* Move Makefile to Makefile.original.  Will eventually merge into the
  new Makefile
* Create new Makefile to handle working in development mode ie python
  will be able to find files in source.  Also handle creating of
  binary releases.
* Create a more python package skeleton ie streamlit/__init__.py  Next
  PRs will move things into this directory.

Fix docker host-mode bug by removing port randomization, and re-joining the client and browser HTTP servers. The bug was: when two containers ran in host mode in the same instance, they would accidentally share the same proxy. To go around this bug, now the user can specify a single proxy port by hand which will apply to both the client and the browser.

commit_message: Added a richer animation example.
Included Thiago's typos.
Move connection/login business logic into ConnectionManager, and get everything working
Re-add Adrien's infinite recursion fix for _create_element exceptions.
Add comment to s3helper.py
Add comments in ConnectionManager.js
Rename fetchManifestAndHandleErrors to fetchManifestWithPossibleLogin
Update version to 0.22.2
Update aws doc on how to upload public ssh key. (#208)
Ignoring node's package-lock.json file because it requires so much babysitting when doing pushes and pulls.
Fixed some bugs Mike Cafarella found in the docs.
Reconciled the final tutorial with the inline example in tutorial2.
Added back in package-lock.json.
Got rid of an unecessary reference to d3-array in package.json.

Create a cloudformation template for easier creation of insight resources for streamlit. (#224)

For #191

Catch caching errors due to large pickle files. (#198)

* Catch caching errors due to large pickle files.

This doesnt fix it but at least gives cleaner error messages.

* Add code review comments.

* Address more code review comments.
Hide logs about .js.map 404
Don't open browser if running inside editor plugin.
Add isRemote+Atom test to config_test.py
Tiny linting: wrap comment to 80chars
Only use console.error when there's an actual error.
Move S3/OAuth constants to baseconsts.js
Fix examples/run_on_save on a Mac
[CSS] Fix header border on Safari
Fix `streamlit kill_proxy` on brew-installed Python, on Mac.
Fix bug where watchdog would suddenly stop working on Mac.
Add comment in __main__.py
Add comments to methods that run in the Observer thread.
Sligth clean up of how we find the proxy process for kill_proxy.
Update package-lock
Re-add hotkeys that got lost by accident in a previous commit.

Make healthz only return ok if a script is connected to the proxy. (#240)

Due to the way the WebSocket Object is created and used, I wasnt sure
that I could set a class instance variable and use it easily in another
location.  So I just made a new class that only has class methods and
variables that way once the script connects via websocket to the proxy,
I can set the ClientWebSocketStatus._is_opened to true and then check it
from the healthz handler very easily.

Fixes #237
Replace GAnalytics with MixPanel (#227)
Make proxy.reportExpirationSecs default to 60s so it's easier to copy/paste the remote URL if needed.
Fix config_test test_config_option_keys()
Only mark proxy as "ready for browser connection" when there's a report registered to it. (#249)

Improve cloudformation template. (#245)

* Improve cloudformation template.

* install rmate
* install a temporary 'streamlit' command that tells the user its still installing.  It will be the real program once its done installing.

* Increase proxy timeout to 120 seconds.

* Add Pull Request comments and also in person comments.

* add lots of comments on what the template is doing.
* remove rmate as we're using sshfs
* change install permissions of config.toml to 755 insteaf of 600
* make changes so script works in python3.6

* Dont create a VPC anymore and use the ones that are already there.
Bump version to 0.24.0

Create ~ubuntu/sshfs directory remotely. (#250)

commit_message:
Add user-tests directory and setup some basic scaffolding for non unit tests.

I know there's an examples and admin already.  This uses the pytest
framework which isn't being heavily used in this example but will be
important later on for the ability to easily reuse mocks, etc.

While this test is trivial, it isn't a unit test.  It actually goes and
uses the internet to check for an ip address which is an integration
test.  We will eventually test more user specific things.
[docs] Add "first things to try" troubleshooting info. (#342)

Rename wrapper annotation in DeltaGenerator, for clarity. (#346)

* Rename wrapper annotation in DeltaGenerator, for clarity.

* Update docstring.
Fix st.add_rows and st.table. Poorly resolved merge conflicts broke them.
Setup fixes; troubleshooting section
Makefile: add 'pytest' help row
Fix deck_gl_chart by passing correct proto.

Fix st.add_rows and st.table. Poorly resolved merge conflicts broke them. (#355)

Fix st.add_rows, st.table, st.deck_gl_chart. Poorly resolved merge conflicts broke them.

increase test_file_watch_and_callback timeout

I can run this test from the commandline no problem, but
it fails in PyCharm (presumably because of slowness from
additional magic that PyCharm inserts when running tests).

Increasing the multiplier to 3 worked for me, but I've set it
to 4 here for extra breathing room on slower machines.

Make vega_lite_chart support inline 'data' and 'dataset' (#347)

* Fix st.add_rows and st.table. Poorly resolved merge conflicts broke them.

* Fix deck_gl_chart by passing correct proto.

* Make vega_lite_chart support inline 'data' and 'dataset'

* Add vega lite unit test

* Deprecate data_transforms in VegaLiteChart.proto

* Clarify vega_lite_example.py

commit_message:
Clear cache (#359)

* frontend: "Clear cache" menu option, dialog, and message sending
* Remove BackMsg.rerun.clear_cache and associated frontend UI
* BackMsg: un-deprecate rerun_script; deprecrate rerun
* eslint: add env.browser=true; some eslint cleanup

clear_cache hotkeys

- 'C' brings up the clear_cache dialog
- enter confirms the dialog

Add Altair support! (#348)

* Fix st.add_rows and st.table. Poorly resolved merge conflicts broke them.

* Fix deck_gl_chart by passing correct proto.

* Add st.altair_chart() and make st.write() accept Pyplot Figures and Altair Charts.

* Add altair to docs and examples

* Add st.altair unit test

* Add altair to pipfile

* Setup fixes; troubleshooting section

* Makefile: add 'pytest' help row

* increase test_file_watch_and_callback timeout

I can run this test from the commandline no problem, but
it fails in PyCharm (presumably because of slowness from
additional magic that PyCharm inserts when running tests).

Increasing the multiplier to 3 worked for me, but I've set it
to 4 here for extra breathing room on slower machines.

* Clear cache (#359)

* frontend: "Clear cache" menu option, dialog, and message sending
* Remove BackMsg.rerun.clear_cache and associated frontend UI
* BackMsg: un-deprecate rerun_script; deprecrate rerun
* eslint: add env.browser=true; some eslint cleanup
Fix docs to point to help@streamlit.io and correct Gradient link.

[circleci] Dont run miniconda or python3.5

These only run on the develop branch.  I removed them and will get added
back when I get to work more on circle ci.
version 0.27.0

Use HTTPs throughout Streamlit codebase and site. (#349)

* Use HTTPs throughout Streamlit codebase and site.

* Make inline docs use https

Remove entrypoints as a dependency in Pipfile now that conda is sorted.

I figured out how conda finally works and this is not necessary.
Also generate the lockfiles for python-*, no need to do it for anaconda
because we won't be using pip install for *conda* in the future.

Add favicon to all site/ and docs/ pages (#369)
[site] Make logo link point to correct URL (#391)

Syntax highlighting (#384)

Uses [Prismjs](https://prismjs.com/) to highlight markdown code blocks.

* `st.code()` wraps the body parameter in markdown codeblock backticks and a language specifier
* `st_markdown()` with codeblock ticks & language specifier will perform syntax highlighting (the CodeBlock react element currently supports javascript, jsx, C-likes, bash/shell, python, sql, json, yaml, css, and HTML; we can add more language support at the cost of a small amount of frontend size)
* `st.echo` calls through to `st.code(value, language='python')`
* `st.write()` also does the right thing

`CodeBlock.css` contains the css styling for the various syntax tokens.

Run `examples/syntax_hilite.py` to see it in action!

st.image() supports URLs (#392)

Fixes https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/issues/367

`st.image` can take a URL string, or list of URL strings, in its first paramater.

(These strings aren't validated, so if you pass in "this is a broken URL" or whatever, it'll just result in a broken image in the report)

Fixes #368

Dont create zombie process when rerunning scripts.

By calling process.wait(), the proxy will cleanup after the script has
ended.  This is non blocking.  I verified by running a long running
script.
* Run mnist-cnn.py
* Click rerun
* While its rerunning went to http://127.0.0.1:8501/healthz and saw in
the debug logs it was hitting the handler with the header timestamp
changing as well as seeing the mnist streamlit output change.

So while it was running I saw this.
```
$ ps -aj | egrep -i 'ppid|python'
USER      PID  PPID  PGID   SESS JOBC STAT   TT       TIME COMMAND
armando 32194 28558 32193      0    2 R+   s002    0:00.00 egrep -i ppid|python
armando 31538     1 31525      0    0 S    s005    0:15.00 /Users/armando/.pyenv/versions/st-psutil/bin/python -m streamlit.proxy
armando 31975 31538 31525      0    0 S    s005    0:00.31 /Users/armando/.pyenv/versions/st-psutil/bin/python -m streamlit run examples/mnist-cnn.py
armando 31976 31975 31525      0    0 R    s005    0:43.17 /Users/armando/.pyenv/versions/st-psutil/bin/python examples/mnist-cnn.py
```

After it was done, no zombie
```
$ ps -aj | egrep -i 'ppid|python'
USER      PID  PPID  PGID   SESS JOBC STAT   TT       TIME COMMAND
armando 32389 28558 32388      0    2 S+   s002    0:00.00 egrep -i ppid|python
armando 31538     1 31525      0    0 S    s005    0:26.73 /Users/armando/.pyenv/versions/st-psutil/bin/python -m streamlit.proxy
```

When you edit a file bar.py on OSX with VI the following events happen

The original file is deleted, a swap file is modified and ignored and then the orignal file is created.
```
2019-03-06T20:40:08Z.059 DEBUG   streamlit.proxy.fs_observer: DELETED: bar.py
2019-03-06T20:40:08Z.059 DEBUG   streamlit.proxy.fs_observer: MODIFIED: .bar.py.swp
2019-03-06T20:40:08Z.059 DEBUG   streamlit.proxy.fs_observer: Ignoring file .bar.py.swp
2019-03-06T20:40:08Z.060 DEBUG   streamlit.proxy.fs_observer: CREATED: bar.py
```

~ Rename on_modified to on_modification so that the handlers on_created,
  on_modified can use the same code.

~ Add back on_modified to call on_modification

Pandas styling (#463)

Adds support for Pandas.Styler CSS styling and custom formatting to `st.dataframe`

Resolves https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/issues/229

Run `python examples/dataframe_styling.py` to see it in action

(See https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/style.html for a Pandas styling primer)

Things to know:
- Dataframe styling data is stored in a `TableStyle` proto that shares the basic structure of DataFrame table data (a list of columns, each of which contains styling data for that column's cells.
- "Styling data" consists of CSS property-value pairs ('color': 'red') and cell display value formatting (e.g. '100.00%' for a cell with value 1.0 that has a percentage formatter applied to it).
- The style parsing code tries to add `CellStyle` data only when there's actual styling applied to a cell. (`dataframe_styling_test.test_unstyled_has_no_style` tests for this.)
- There are several unfortunate instances of protected-member access of the Pandas.Styler object, because none of the Pandas styling stuff is designed to be consumed by code.
- We don't really support the `DataFrame.style.bar` bar chart styling: bar charts modify the widths of their cells, and the frontend `DataFrame.jsx.getWidths()` function doesn't currently consider css styling data to determine cell widths. I think we could add this, but it'd be a bit of a pain, so I'm punting on it since the user who requested styling wasn't looking for bar chart support.

Proxy refactoring, "ReportSession" object #538

This does some Proxy cleanup and refactoring to set the stage for the run-on-save UI improvements that are coming down the line:

- ForwardMsg schema change
    + `NewConnection` -> `Initialize`
    + `NewReportMessage` -> `NewReport`
    + Added `SessionState`, for session state changed events
- `ForwardMsg`s get composed in `forward_msg_proto.py`
- A few things in Proxy got moved around:
    + `Proxy._connections` -> `Proxy._proxy_connections`
    + `Proxy.register_browser()`, `Proxy.deregister_browser()` -> `Proxy.register_browser_with_report_queue()`
- Proxy no longer has `_get_file_path()`. Instead, `ProxyConnection.source_file_path` is initialized with the proper path to watch for report changes.
- Proxy browser registration is now consolidated into `on_browser_connection_opened`, which implements the following sequence of events:
    + Send the `Initialize` ForwardMsg to the browser
    + Register the browser with report_queue (sends the `NewReport` ForwardMsg)
    + Register with `ReportSession`, creating it if it doesn't exist
    + Register BrowserWebSocket to ReportSession's signal listeners
- Inverse happens in `on_browser_connection_closed`

There's only a small bit of new functionality in this PR: "run-on-save" state changes are now synchronized between all connected browsers. (So if two browsers are viewing the same report, and one of them toggles the run-on-save setting for that report, the other browser will be notified of this change.)

ReportSession event plumbing (#549)

This adds plumbing to Proxy and frontend to support upcoming run-on-save improvements:

- `ReportSession` always watches its report's source_file. If that file changes, and run-on-save is not enabled for the report, a `SessionEvent` ForwardMsg will be delivered to connected browsers. (This currently just results in the event being logged to the browser's console.)
- `ReportSession` knows about the current `ProxyConnection` for its report, and it monitors its ProxyConnection to determine when its report is being run. ReportSession's state object has a new boolean, `report_is_running` that stores this value. When this value changes, a `session_state_changed` message will be delivered to connected browsers, containing this value.
- The `SessionEvent` protobuf message also has support for a future `report_was_manually_stopped` event, though this isn't implemented yet.

(Future improvement proposal: `ProxyConnection` feels like it should probably now be managed entirely by `ReportSession`, rather than by `Proxy`.)

Proxy refactoring, "ReportSession" object #538

This does some Proxy cleanup and refactoring to set the stage for the run-on-save UI improvements that are coming down the line:

- ForwardMsg schema change
    + `NewConnection` -> `Initialize`
    + `NewReportMessage` -> `NewReport`
    + Added `SessionState`, for session state changed events
- `ForwardMsg`s get composed in `forward_msg_proto.py`
- A few things in Proxy got moved around:
    + `Proxy._connections` -> `Proxy._proxy_connections`
    + `Proxy.register_browser()`, `Proxy.deregister_browser()` -> `Proxy.register_browser_with_report_queue()`
- Proxy no longer has `_get_file_path()`. Instead, `ProxyConnection.source_file_path` is initialized with the proper path to watch for report changes.
- Proxy browser registration is now consolidated into `on_browser_connection_opened`, which implements the following sequence of events:
    + Send the `Initialize` ForwardMsg to the browser
    + Register the browser with report_queue (sends the `NewReport` ForwardMsg)
    + Register with `ReportSession`, creating it if it doesn't exist
    + Register BrowserWebSocket to ReportSession's signal listeners
- Inverse happens in `on_browser_connection_closed`

There's only a small bit of new functionality in this PR: "run-on-save" state changes are now synchronized between all connected browsers. (So if two browsers are viewing the same report, and one of them toggles the run-on-save setting for that report, the other browser will be notified of this change.)

Fix bug where stats for shared reports were not being tracked. (#544)

* Fix bug where stats for shared reports were not being tracked.

* Change mixpanel fix to check for static connection.

ReportSession event plumbing (#549)

This adds plumbing to Proxy and frontend to support upcoming run-on-save improvements:

- `ReportSession` always watches its report's source_file. If that file changes, and run-on-save is not enabled for the report, a `SessionEvent` ForwardMsg will be delivered to connected browsers. (This currently just results in the event being logged to the browser's console.)
- `ReportSession` knows about the current `ProxyConnection` for its report, and it monitors its ProxyConnection to determine when its report is being run. ReportSession's state object has a new boolean, `report_is_running` that stores this value. When this value changes, a `session_state_changed` message will be delivered to connected browsers, containing this value.
- The `SessionEvent` protobuf message also has support for a future `report_was_manually_stopped` event, though this isn't implemented yet.

(Future improvement proposal: `ProxyConnection` feels like it should probably now be managed entirely by `ReportSession`, rather than by `Proxy`.)

* Proxy refactoring, "ReportSession" object #538

This does some Proxy cleanup and refactoring to set the stage for the run-on-save UI improvements that are coming down the line:

- ForwardMsg schema change
    + `NewConnection` -> `Initialize`
    + `NewReportMessage` -> `NewReport`
    + Added `SessionState`, for session state changed events
- `ForwardMsg`s get composed in `forward_msg_proto.py`
- A few things in Proxy got moved around:
    + `Proxy._connections` -> `Proxy._proxy_connections`
    + `Proxy.register_browser()`, `Proxy.deregister_browser()` -> `Proxy.register_browser_with_report_queue()`
- Proxy no longer has `_get_file_path()`. Instead, `ProxyConnection.source_file_path` is initialized with the proper path to watch for report changes.
- Proxy browser registration is now consolidated into `on_browser_connection_opened`, which implements the following sequence of events:
    + Send the `Initialize` ForwardMsg to the browser
    + Register the browser with report_queue (sends the `NewReport` ForwardMsg)
    + Register with `ReportSession`, creating it if it doesn't exist
    + Register BrowserWebSocket to ReportSession's signal listeners
- Inverse happens in `on_browser_connection_closed`

There's only a small bit of new functionality in this PR: "run-on-save" state changes are now synchronized between all connected browsers. (So if two browsers are viewing the same report, and one of them toggles the run-on-save setting for that report, the other browser will be notified of this change.)

* ReportSession event plumbing (#549)

This adds plumbing to Proxy and frontend to support upcoming run-on-save improvements:

- `ReportSession` always watches its report's source_file. If that file changes, and run-on-save is not enabled for the report, a `SessionEvent` ForwardMsg will be delivered to connected browsers. (This currently just results in the event being logged to the browser's console.)
- `ReportSession` knows about the current `ProxyConnection` for its report, and it monitors its ProxyConnection to determine when its report is being run. ReportSession's state object has a new boolean, `report_is_running` that stores this value. When this value changes, a `session_state_changed` message will be delivered to connected browsers, containing this value.
- The `SessionEvent` protobuf message also has support for a future `report_was_manually_stopped` event, though this isn't implemented yet.

(Future improvement proposal: `ProxyConnection` feels like it should probably now be managed entirely by `ReportSession`, rather than by `Proxy`.)

Report changed prompt: collapse/uncollapse (#608)

Makes some improvements to the "Source file changed. Rerun?" prompt.

- After being displayed for 15 seconds, the prompt collapses down to an icon
- If the user hovers over the collapsed icon, the prompt un-collapses. (The ticket originally asked for this to happen on click, instead of hover; that's an easy change if it's still the desired behavior, but this seemed a bit more expected?)
- The uncollapsed-on-hover icon will recollapse again after the mouse hasn't hovered over it for 1 second

StatusWidget: fade-in/out animations (#615)

Adds a fade-in and fade-out to StatusWidget appearance and disappearance.

StatusWidget now has a top-level `CSSTransition` element, via the [ReactTransitionGroup](https://github.com/reactjs/react-transition-group) library. It wraps the StatusWidget's actual display elements, and adds/removes the CSS classes that perform the animations automatically.

(We should consider using ReactTransitionGroup to control other bits of animation in the code; it's elegant and simple.)

Fade out stale elements on report rerun (#655)

- Report rendering is broken out of `StreamlitApp` and is now handled by a `ReportView` component

* Proxy refactoring, "ReportSession" object #538

This does some Proxy cleanup and refactoring to set the stage for the run-on-save UI improvements that are coming down the line:

- ForwardMsg schema change
    + `NewConnection` -> `Initialize`
    + `NewReportMessage` -> `NewReport`
    + Added `SessionState`, for session state changed events
- `ForwardMsg`s get composed in `forward_msg_proto.py`
- A few things in Proxy got moved around:
    + `Proxy._connections` -> `Proxy._proxy_connections`
    + `Proxy.register_browser()`, `Proxy.deregister_browser()` -> `Proxy.register_browser_with_report_queue()`
- Proxy no longer has `_get_file_path()`. Instead, `ProxyConnection.source_file_path` is initialized with the proper path to watch for report changes.
- Proxy browser registration is now consolidated into `on_browser_connection_opened`, which implements the following sequence of events:
    + Send the `Initialize` ForwardMsg to the browser
    + Register the browser with report_queue (sends the `NewReport` ForwardMsg)
    + Register with `ReportSession`, creating it if it doesn't exist
    + Register BrowserWebSocket to ReportSession's signal listeners
- Inverse happens in `on_browser_connection_closed`

There's only a small bit of new functionality in this PR: "run-on-save" state changes are now synchronized between all connected browsers. (So if two browsers are viewing the same report, and one of them toggles the run-on-save setting for that report, the other browser will be notified of this change.)

* ReportSession event plumbing (#549)

This adds plumbing to Proxy and frontend to support upcoming run-on-save improvements:

- `ReportSession` always watches its report's source_file. If that file changes, and run-on-save is not enabled for the report, a `SessionEvent` ForwardMsg will be delivered to connected browsers. (This currently just results in the event being logged to the browser's console.)
- `ReportSession` knows about the current `ProxyConnection` for its report, and it monitors its ProxyConnection to determine when its report is being run. ReportSession's state object has a new boolean, `report_is_running` that stores this value. When this value changes, a `session_state_changed` message will be delivered to connected browsers, containing this value.
- The `SessionEvent` protobuf message also has support for a future `report_was_manually_stopped` event, though this isn't implemented yet.

(Future improvement proposal: `ProxyConnection` feels like it should probably now be managed entirely by `ReportSession`, rather than by `Proxy`.)

* Proxy refactoring, "ReportSession" object #538

This does some Proxy cleanup and refactoring to set the stage for the run-on-save UI improvements that are coming down the line:

- ForwardMsg schema change
    + `NewConnection` -> `Initialize`
    + `NewReportMessage` -> `NewReport`
    + Added `SessionState`, for session state changed events
- `ForwardMsg`s get composed in `forward_msg_proto.py`
- A few things in Proxy got moved around:
    + `Proxy._connections` -> `Proxy._proxy_connections`
    + `Proxy.register_browser()`, `Proxy.deregister_browser()` -> `Proxy.register_browser_with_report_queue()`
- Proxy no longer has `_get_file_path()`. Instead, `ProxyConnection.source_file_path` is initialized with the proper path to watch for report changes.
- Proxy browser registration is now consolidated into `on_browser_connection_opened`, which implements the following sequence of events:
    + Send the `Initialize` ForwardMsg to the browser
    + Register the browser with report_queue (sends the `NewReport` ForwardMsg)
    + Register with `ReportSession`, creating it if it doesn't exist
    + Register BrowserWebSocket to ReportSession's signal listeners
- Inverse happens in `on_browser_connection_closed`

There's only a small bit of new functionality in this PR: "run-on-save" state changes are now synchronized between all connected browsers. (So if two browsers are viewing the same report, and one of them toggles the run-on-save setting for that report, the other browser will be notified of this change.)

* ReportSession event plumbing (#549)

This adds plumbing to Proxy and frontend to support upcoming run-on-save improvements:

- `ReportSession` always watches its report's source_file. If that file changes, and run-on-save is not enabled for the report, a `SessionEvent` ForwardMsg will be delivered to connected browsers. (This currently just results in the event being logged to the browser's console.)
- `ReportSession` knows about the current `ProxyConnection` for its report, and it monitors its ProxyConnection to determine when its report is being run. ReportSession's state object has a new boolean, `report_is_running` that stores this value. When this value changes, a `session_state_changed` message will be delivered to connected browsers, containing this value.
- The `SessionEvent` protobuf message also has support for a future `report_was_manually_stopped` event, though this isn't implemented yet.

(Future improvement proposal: `ProxyConnection` feels like it should probably now be managed entirely by `ReportSession`, rather than by `Proxy`.)

commit_message: [0px] Fix remaining tests by improving conftest.py

Frontend: simplify SessionEventDispatcher (#705)

This changes a couple things about `ForwardMsg` handling on the frontend:

- `StreamlitApp.handleMessage` only passes `Delta` messages through immutableJS; all other message types are unmodified.
- `ReportEventDispatcher` is now called `SessionEventDispatcher`. It receives `SessionEvent` protobuf messages from StreamlitApp and redispatches them via a signal. (Previously, ReportEventDispatcher was maintaining a "ReportEvent" enum that just mapped SessionEvent types to enum values. Now we skip that extra bookkeeping.)

Show a modal dialog on script compilation failure (#715)

- `SessionEvent` gets a new `scriptCompilationFailed` type
- When ScriptRunner fails to compile its script, it emits a signal and exits the `_run` loop 
- Server catches this script compilation failed signal and delivers `SessionEvent.scriptCompilationFailed` to the frontend
- On the frontend, scriptCompilationFailed results in a new dialog being shown, and a flag being set that prevents the previous report's elements from being cleared when the ReportRunState changes to NOT_RUNNING (which will follow the exception message immediately.)

ScriptRunner thread safety (#811)

Refactors ScriptRunner to be thread safe

- ScriptRunner state change requests (`STOP`, `RERUN` and `SHUTDOWN`) are made through its `ScriptEventQueue`.
- Multiple `RERUN` requests are coalesced in the event queue, so only the most recent RERUN request will be in the queue.
- ScriptRunner's run-thread is created immediately, and is no longer shut down between script runs. 
- The run thread consumes ScriptEvents from the event queue. If the queue is empty, the thread waits on a condition variable until the queue has an event.
- The run thread is the only thread that ever mutates `ScriptRunner._state`
- The unused PAUSE event is gone

Attach widget state to RERUN event (#820)

- `Report.argv` can no longer be mutated. Instead, each RERUN can optionally override the `argv` value
- RERUN events also have `widget_state` attached to them. This gets passed into the Widget singleton at the same time the report is being re-run, so widget state stays in sync with script execution (and a widget-initiated rerun request will resolve with the proper set of widget values).

Multiuser i9e (#875)

With this change, each connected browser has its own widget state, delta generator, and ability to rerun reports independently.

- A new `ReportContext` is created for each connected browser
- Each `ReportContext` encapsulates its own DeltaGenerator, ScriptRunner, Widget dictionary, Report, and ReportQueues
- Each thread involved in a running report has the appropriate `ReportContext` attached to it. The streamlit lib's `_with_dg` wrapper finds the appropriate DeltaGenerator by examining the current thread's ReportContext. (There's no longer a global root DeltaGenerator.)
- The `_widget` wrapper inside `DeltaGenerator.py` does the same thing to find the appropriate Widget state dictionary.
- Much of `Server`'s logic is now inside ReportContext. Server is mostly responsible for creating new ReportContexts when browsers connect, and tearing the contexts down when browsers disconnect.
- Server is now responsible for shutting down the ioloop (this happens at the end of its run loop). The bootstrap signal handler requests a stop from the server, which (ultimately) results in all threads being closed and the ioloop stopped.

Closes https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/issues/832

Resend widget values when the browser reconnects to the server (after the server has shut down and restarted) so that our displayed widget values aren't stale.

Fixes #940

[i9e] Button state coalescing (#1005)

When multiple RERUN requests are received by the server, any `trigger_values` that were set in the older request will be preserved in the new, coalesced request, to prevent button clicks from going un-handled.

Also, I added a handful of Widget and ScriptEventQueue tests 'cause we didn't have any yet.

commit_message:
empty_dataframes e2e test (#988)

Tests empty dataframe/empty table rendering

Fix coalescing widget state with None (#1018)

Rerun requests can submit "None" for their widget_data, which
means "rerun with the previous run's widget values." This wasn't
being handled before.

Update the vega_lite_chart e2e test with snapshots (#1011)

It turns out there was already a bare-bones vega_lite e2e test, so I didn't create one from scratch.

Instead, I merged `examples/vega_lite_example.py` into `core/vega_lite_chart.py`, and deleted the former file. 

`vega_lite_chart.spec.ts` now tests snapshots for the various chart types

Closes #882
pipfile.lock

Rerun request coalescing bug, take 2 (#1025)

This is an embarrassing followup to https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/pull/1018.

That PR fixed one of the two edge cases involved in Rerun request coalescing. This PR fixes the other one: coalescing a `RerunRequest` with a null `widget_state` into an existing `RerunRequest` with a non-null widget_state. Test is included.

I also snuck in a tiny change to Server and ScriptRunner, to extend State classes from `Enum` instead of `object`, which is Slightly More Correct.

ScriptRunner improvements and tests (#1115)

- A number of types got renamed:
    - `ReportContext` -> `ReportSession`
    - `ReportContext` still exists, but as a simple namedtuple that just contains a `DeltaGenerator` and `Widgets`, and is attached to ReportThreads
    - `ScriptEventQueue` -> `ScriptRequestQueue`
    - `ScriptState` is now `ScriptRunnerEvent` (and is no longer a "state")
- ScriptRunner shuts down its thread after it processes everything in `ScriptRequestQueue`
- `ScriptRunner` and `ReportSession` have well-defined channels of communication, and otherwise have no shared state:
    - ReportSession-to-ScriptRunner requests go through a `ScriptRequestQueue`, with the exception of `maybe_handle_execution_control_request`, which works as before
    - ScriptRunner-to-ReportSession communication happens through `ScriptRunnerEvent`s which are emitted via ScriptRunner.on_event. (These events fire on ScriptRunner's run thread, so ReportSession needs to be careful about running its event handling logic on the main thread, by way of ioloop, when appropriate.)
    - ReportSession no longer exposes its internals (Widgets dict is managed by ScriptRunner, and ReportSession passes the initial widget state on ScriptRunner creation; LocalSourcesWatcher is managed by ReportSession and never exposed to ScriptRunner)
- `ScriptRunnerTest` tests all (I think!) script running scenarios, except for some of the more exotic magic stuff (`runner.installTracer` and `runner.magicEnabled` aren't tested yet).

(We should be able to easily use a `ThreadPoolExecutor` for ScriptRunner threads now, if that's still desirable.)

Speed up webpack with caching (#1184)

The big thing here is `HardSourceWebpackPlugin` (https://github.com/mzgoddard/hard-source-webpack-plugin) which speeds up webpack dramatically once the cache is created.

On my machine, with a warm hard-source cache, `yarn start` takes about 8 seconds (down from 21), and `make build` takes about 35 seconds (down from 53).

I also pruned a couple unused dependencies (lodash and static-eval) - though sadly both of these are used transitively, so this doesn't buy us any reduction in dependency count.

Finally, `make all` no longer cleans the project, so we won't accidentally blow away the various generated bits that make builds less painfully slow.

Testable server (#1257)

Implements basic testing architecture for the Server class, and adds a few simple Server tests.

Because of the async nature of the server, this is more complex than a typical test would be. Some of that complexity is abstracted into the "ServerTestCase" class, but tests themselves also need to jump through some hoops to work with ioloop.

This involved some minor changes to Server:
- Server now takes its ioloop in its constructor
- Server shuts down the ioloop in a separate function, so that the test base class can patch out this function and prevent the ioloop from being closed (the tests need to manage the ioloop's lifetime)
- Server starting no longer happens in server init; the test needs to manage the server starting process.

Adding width and height parameter to st.dataframe (#33)

This PR proposes to add a width and height parameter to st.dataframe. Protobuf is changed to include an ElementDimensionSpec field to carry this information. This is included as part of the forward message metadata. The message is parsed and height/width information is extracted and passed down to the Dataframe React component in Block.tsx. Width is set in Block.tsx since existing logic applies to a generic element, while height is set in the Dataframe element in some ad hoc logic.

commit_message:
Check version on startup (#106)

Occasionally check the installed streamlit version against the latest in PyPI, and show a notice if there's a new version available.

The check runs randomly with a 5% chance, so that we're not spamming the user frequently.

I used `requests` (instead of urllib) for this, which entailed adding it as an explicit dependency in our Pipfile. All the other places in streamlit that used urllib for fetching over HTTP have been replaced with requests. (And there are some additional tests that didn't previously exist.)

Fixes #65

Fixed broken websocket when reconnect (#105)

* Fixed broken websocket when reconnect

* Cleaning doHealthPing()

Adding `streamlit run` by url (#99)

* Adding `streamlit run` by url

Test running streamlit commands "bare" (#133)

- Adds a new test step to CircleCI: "Run Integration Tests", and an associated Make rule `make integration-tests`
- This runs `scripts/run_bare_integration_tests.py`, which runs all the e2e tests in "bare" mode - that is, via `python script.py` instead of `streamlit run script.py`. The test script ensures that all the e2e scripts exit with a zero exit code.
- Streamlit detects if it's running in bare mode via a new global, `_is_running_with_streamlit`. This defaults to false, and gets set to true by the `streamlit run` CLI command.
- When running in bare mode, streamlit does not show "missing ReportContext" warnings.
- This PR also pins the streamlit numpy dependency to < 1.17 when installed in a Python 2 environment; numpy 1.17 dropped support for Py2.

Merge ForwardMsg caching into develop  (#178)

Implements ForwardMsg caching on the client and server.

## Server

- `ForwardMsg.hash` is calculated on every outgoing ForwardMsg
- The server caches all messages whose size is >= 10k in its `MessageCache` instance. (These cached message are never evicted - this will come in a future PR.) Each entry in the cache contains the cached message, and also a (weak-referenced) set of all ReportSessions for which that message has already been delivered.
- Cached ForwardMsgs have the `metadata.cacheable` flag set. When the client receives a ForwardMsg with `cacheable == true`, it also caches it.
- If the server believes that a client has cached a given ForwardMsg (because the cache has an entry for that message+session), it instead sends a "reference" message that points to the original message via `ForwardMsg.ref_hash`.
- The server also exposes a new HTTP endpoint, `/message`, from which clients can request messages that they have received a `ref_hash` message for, but are missing in that client's local cache. (This should not happen frequently! If clients are getting a bunch of local cache misses, then the server is not maintaining its cache properly.)

## Client

- `WebsocketConnection` has a new `ForwardMsgCache` member
- All incoming `ForwardMsgs` are passed through this cache (via `ForwardMsgCache.processMessage`):
  - If the ForwardMsg is *not* a reference message, it is cached locally and nothing more is done
  - If the ForwardMsg *is* a reference message, the client checks to see if it has the original message in its cache; if so, it gets returned
  - If the reference message is missing from the client's cache, it is requested from the server's `/message` endpoint, and then cached.

## Cache expiration

- The `global.maxCachedMessageAge` config value specifies the maximum age of a message in the cache. The age of a message is defined by the number of times a referencing report has finished running since the message was accessed by that report. So when a report finishes running for the first time, the age of all its cached messages is 1.
- Our default maxCachedMessageAge is 2, which means that messages will remain cached even after not having been referenced for a report run.
- To determine the age of messages in its cache, the server tracks a `report_run_count` alongside each `ReportSession` in its websocket->reportsession dictionary. The server increments this value each time it processes a `report_finished` ForwardMsg message for a report.
- When the server increments `report_finished`, it also asks the cache to remove any expired messages. I haven't done anything fancy here - the cache just iterates through all its entries, does an age check, and deletes them if they're expired.
- Similarly, when the client receives a `report_finished` ForwardMsg, it performs the same cache expiration step. This means that the server and client's caches should stay in sync. (I haven't thought hard enough about whether it's possible for them to get briefly out of sync, but if they do, we have the new `/message` endpoint as a fallback.)
- If a report fails to run due to a compilation error, neither the server nor the client will increment the `report_run_count` for that session. (The run-count incrementing is conditional on the status value of the `report_finished` message, which is set to `FINISHED_WITH_COMPILE_ERROR` when that happens.)


There are client and server tests for all this new logic. But the easiest way to see the expiration in action is to run something like `examples/core/message_deduping.py` and watch the debug output on the server and the client. (You'll see logs for cache hits and misses - you should never see a miss! - on the client; and logs for sending cached message refs on the server.)
- This example just creates a big dataframe and sends it twice
- The first time the report is run, the message will only be delivered to the client once.
- If you rerun the report, the message won't be delivered at all because it'll be cached.
- If you remove the `st.dataframe()` calls and rerun the report, the dataframe will *not* be removed from the cache because it won't be old enough. Re-adding those calls and rerunning the report should confirm this.
- If you remove the dataframe calls and re-run the report _twice_ with them missing, they will then be expired from the cache. Re-adding them should result in the message being resent to the client.

Read config from ${CWD}/.streamlit/config.toml (#227)

If a project has a config.toml at `${cwd}/.streamlit/config.toml`, it's merged with the global config.toml (with the local config taking precedence for any options that are defined twice).

This also makes some minor API changes:

- `util.get_streamlit_file_path` no longer intermediate directories for the file. Instead, the few places that need to ensure those directories exist call `os.makedirs` when appropriate.
- `config.parse_config_file` no longer takes an optional `file_contents` param. This was only used for tests; the tests now properly patch the `os.open` `os.path.exists` and `os.makedirs` calls.

Tim/static sharing redux (#332)

Fixes static sharing, and re-enables it in the frontend.

- The static manifest is now a `StaticManifest` protobuf object, rather than an untyped json.
- The manifest no longer contains "num_deltas" and "first_delta_index" properties, and deltas no longer get new indexes assigned when a report is shared. This scheme doesn't play well with sidebar and blocks, which didn't exist when the sharing option was conceived.
- If sharing is not enabled, then the option is hidden (rather than simply disabled) in the Main Menu. (This is per @tvst's request.)
- I fixed an unrelated issue in `config_test.test_browser_server_port` that kept popping up while writing tests for this new functionality, so that's why those bits are in there.
- The "Upload Complete" dialog has a few tweaks: the URL is styled in a `<pre>`, and is clickable. There's also a new "Open" button in that dialog.

(I tested this with the `[server] liveSave = true` option set as well.)

Widgets with identical IDs raise an Exception (#425)

- When two widgets with the same ID are encountered in a report run, we throw a DuplicateWidgetID exception. The exception tells the user that they can use the new optional "key" parameter that each widget now takes in order to fix the issue.
- (The error is slightly different if the user has manually supplied an identical key to multiple widgets.)
- To track widget keys, `ReportContext` has a new `widget_ids_this_run` set. Each time a widget has an ID assigned, we add that ID to the set. If the ID was already in the set, the exception is thrown. (Because it's possible to access this set from multiple threads, access to it is wrapped in a `threading.Lock`).
- `ScriptRunner` clears the `widget_ids_this_run` right before running its script.
- If you supply a custom widget key, the actual widget id becomes `"{user-key}-{element-hash}"`). This maintains the rule that if you change a widget's signature, you get a different widget ID.

Workaround for deep import reloads not working (#537)

**Issue:** https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/issues/366

Fixes #366, #358

**Description:** 
This is a sketch for now, we may want to look at a more sophisticated fix. Although it does fix the linked issue, it does so in a somewhat scorched-earth manner.

Essentially what is happening is that if you have a module which is not directly imported by the base module (e.g.` app.py` imports `a.py`, `a.py` imports `b.py`), then changes to that module will not be reloaded when a file change is detected.

As far as I can understand, this is what is happening:
- User changes `b.py`
- Reload logic:
  - Deletes `b` from `sys.modules`
  - Calls eval on the code from `app.py`
  - The code in `app.py` imports `a`, which is already present in `sys.modules`, and so we are done
  - The result is that we keep using the old copy of `b` in memory until `a` is reloaded

The ideal solution would be to unload both the modified module, as well as any modules that are importing it, but determining this tree of all possible paths for importing a given module may not be worth the effort.

Instead, what this PR does is simply unloads all watched modules. So in the scenario above, `a` gets unloaded as well when `b` changes, and so at the eval point both modules get reloaded, therefore reflecting the changes to `b` in the running app.

Nicer frontend exception display (#490)

- Defines a new exception class, `StreamlitAPIException`, that's used for exceptions resulting from improper usage of the streamlit API. (That is, `StreamlitAPIException` is meant for "user errors", like calling a DeltaGenerator function with bad inputs.)
- `Exception.proto` has a new field, `message_is_markdown`, which is True when the exception being sent is a `StreamlitAPIException` instance. Markdown formatting in the exception message will be nicely rendered on the frontend.
- `StreamlitAPIException` stack traces get all Streamlit entries pruned before being marshalled into the exception proto. This means that when a user misuses a Streamlit API, they no longer see a bunch of ScriptRunner and DeltaGenerator lines in the stack trace we show them.
- I updated most (all?) user-facing errors to use StreamlitAPIException, for the nicer formatting.
- Non-API-related errors, originating from the bowels of Streamlit, will _not_ be specially pruned/formatted, so this shouldn't hinder us when debugging Streamlit itself.

__E901,E999,F821,F822,F823__ are the "_showstopper_" [flake8](http://flake8.pycqa.org) issues that can halt the runtime with a SyntaxError, NameError, etc. These 5 are different from most other flake8 issues which are merely "style violations" -- useful for readability but they do not effect runtime safety.
* F821: undefined name `name`
* F822: undefined name `name` in `__all__`
* F823: local variable name referenced before assignment
* E901: SyntaxError or IndentationError
* E999: SyntaxError -- failed to compile a file into an Abstract Syntax Tree

* Nicer frontend exception display (#490)

- Defines a new exception class, `StreamlitAPIException`, that's used for exceptions resulting from improper usage of the streamlit API. (That is, `StreamlitAPIException` is meant for "user errors", like calling a DeltaGenerator function with bad inputs.)
- `Exception.proto` has a new field, `message_is_markdown`, which is True when the exception being sent is a `StreamlitAPIException` instance. Markdown formatting in the exception message will be nicely rendered on the frontend.
- `StreamlitAPIException` stack traces get all Streamlit entries pruned before being marshalled into the exception proto. This means that when a user misuses a Streamlit API, they no longer see a bunch of ScriptRunner and DeltaGenerator lines in the stack trace we show them.
- I updated most (all?) user-facing errors to use StreamlitAPIException, for the nicer formatting.
- Non-API-related errors, originating from the bowels of Streamlit, will _not_ be specially pruned/formatted, so this shouldn't hinder us when debugging Streamlit itself.

Fix the "keyPrefix" option in static report sharing (#724)

This fixes an issue where using a `keyPrefix` with a `/` in it would result in the frontend failing to download a statically shared report.

The issue was pretty simple - we were just doing some naive string parsing in `ConnectionManager` and `StaticConnection`. This fix implements the correct parsing in a new function called `getBucketAndResourceRoot`; both `ConnectionManager` and `StaticConnection` use this new function instead of implementing the (broken) logic themselves.

UNRELATED to this PR are a handful of `pylint` fixes; CircleCI was failing my build because of some formatting in a few python files. They had to come along for the ride to make Circle happy :/

Display area/bar/line chart time values in UTC, rather than browser-local time (#621)

By default, vega-lite displays time data in the browser's local time zone, regardless of which time zone the data specifies. (See https://vega.github.io/vega-lite/docs/timeunit.html#output for more details.) This leads to unexpected results - see #485 for an example.

With this PR, for generated altair charts (`st.area`, `bar`, `line`), we now explicitly set the X and Y axes' scale to `type="utc"` if they contain `datetime.date` values. This is meaningful only for date/time values, but it means that time data will be shown in UTC, rather the user's local time zone.

WebsocketConnection: handle fatal errors (#752)

Currently, if there's some sort of fatal error in WebsocketConnection, it hangs and doesn't display anything meaningful to the user. These changes fix that:

- The "CONNECTION_WTF" event is now called "FATAL_ERROR", and is properly handled. 
- If we receive this event from any FSM state, we transition to the "DISCONNECTED_FOREVER" state and send along an error message to ConnectionManager.
- These error messages are now displayed in the "Connection Error" dialog. (Previously, the dialog would just say "Unknown".)

NumberInput format string fixes (#799)

1. Fixes `NumberInput` so that it doesn't explode on malformed format strings. `sprintf` throws an exception if the format string is bad, and we're currently not handling this, so a bad format string will just crash the Streamlit page.

2. Clarify the `DeltaGenerator.number_input` format doc a bit.

The frontend uses `sprintf`, which does not really support Python-style format strings, so I removed that bit of text.

(sprintf _does_ support named parameters, but the user has no control over the params that get passed to the sprintf function (there's only one param, and it's the value of the number input), so this distinction is not meaningful here.)

Ensure that s3.url is an absolute URL (#828)

If `s3.url` is set in the user's config, ensure that it's an absolute URL.

An absolute URL starts with either `scheme://` or `//` -- if the configured URL does not start with either prefix, prepend it with `//` to make it absolute. (If we don't do this, and the user enters something like `url=myhost.com/reports`, the browser will assume this is a relative URL, and will prepend the hostname of the Streamlit instance to the configured URL.)

Fix st.empty breakage inside shared reports (#871)

### Background

Currently, using `st.empty()` (or `st.cache`/`st.spinner`, which use `st.empty` internally) will break static sharing because of recent changes to the frontend. Specifically, the frontend now requires that delta IDs start from 0 and increment by 1 for each new delta in each container. 

Because we remove `st.empty` deltas from serialized reports, we break the implicit "sequential delta ID" rule, and the frontend crashes when trying to view a shared report that used `st.empty`. This example app will demonstrate the breakage: run the app, share it, and try to view the shared report:

```python
import streamlit as st
st.empty()
st.write("I'm not shareable!")
```

### This PR

This PR does a few things. The most basic and important thing is:

- `st.empty`s are no longer stripped from shared reports. (Fixes #827, which is the original motivation here.)

To facilitate that, it also does a few other things:

- `global.sharingMode="file"` is now a supported config option. If you use this sharing mode, your protobufs will be serialized to `frontend/public/reports`, which allows them to be served by the dev server. This is obviously not intended for users; while it's not harmful if they use it, `config.py` now emits a warning upon config loading if this option is set and `global.developmentMode` is not. (This means that testing changes to static sharing no longer requires the "`make build` -> run app -> Share to S3 -> try to debug minified javascript" routine; you can do it all from the devserver.)
- The frontend StaticConnection code has been refactored and simplified a bit to account for the new sharing mode.
- There's now a test for `ReportSession.handle_save_request` that ensures the serialized data is what we expect.

I've not added `frontend/public/reports` to the `.gitignore`, which means that if you use `global.sharingMode="file"`, you'll end up with a bunch of uncommitted serialized report data in your frontend folder. You should remove these before doing a `make build` so that they don't end up in a PyPI wheel file or anything. (`make clean` will remove them.)

### Next steps

The "strip st.empty deltas out of shared reports" functionality was in Streamlit to prevent serialization of the st.empty's that get auto-created by `st.cache`. Since we'd still like to prevent cache-induced serialization spam, the next step is to change `st.spinner` (which st.cache uses, and which is what actually creates the additional empties) to be more clever, and probably not involve delta-creation at all.

Slider, NumberInput: store values in doubles (#960)

- `Slider` and `NumberInput` store int *and* float value data in doubles.
-- For int data, we no longer use `int32` (too small) or `int64` (no point, since JavaScript Number supports ints only up to 2^53, `double` can represent those ints with no precision loss, and our Base UI widgets don't support BigInts).
-- For float data, we no longer use `float` (too small).
- On the Python side, there's a new utility class called `JSNumber` that does bounds checking on int/float data that's destined for JS. We use this for additional validation in st.slider/st.number_input.

Fixes #764 (though not in the method described in the issue; we decided to simplify everything with double instead of using sint64).

Improve docs (#1075)

* Improve docs.

* Apostrophes

Add CircleCI jobs to run the oldest and newest Python versions we support. (#1053)

As part of this, we've removed the per-Python-version lib/Pipfile.locks/
files in favor of running without pipenv lock files, and having CircleCI
cache our Python environment using a combination of the Python binary,
lib/Pipfile, and the current data.

This implies that once per day we'll potentially upgrade our Python
packages, consistent with any requirements in lib/Pipfile. We will
always regenerate our Python environment if lib/Pipfile changes,
potentially upgrading any other packages at that time as well. This was
deemed acceptable in a conversation with @tvst.

This also introduces tests.testutils.requires_tensorflow(), a decorator
for tests that require Tensorflow, so that we can skip these under
Python 3.8, which Tensorflow does not yet support.

In doing this work, it was discovered that we had broken our support for
Python 3.5. This required two fixes:

o Invocations of "black" were modified to tell it that it needs
  to retain support for Python 3.5 syntax, which does not permit a
  trailing comma after "**kwargs" in a function definition. Fixed this in
  two places in DeltaGenerator.py, restoring Python 3.5 support.

o In e2e/scripts/st_magic.py, tests of async generators were made
  conditional on Python 3.6 or greater.

Following this change I expect one follow-up commit, and I made a few
voluntary style changes:

o Once this makes it to master, I expect to change the
  "fully-specified" job from python-3.7.4 to python-3.8, leaving only
  one "inheriting" job at 3.5. Not doing this yet so we can get the new
  name passing before we change out GitHub status checks to reference it.

o The new job names reference the Python major and minor versions they
  belong to, but *not* the micro version (e.g., 4 in 3.7.4). I think we
  should be able to advance along these micro/maintenance releases
  without switching job names.

o In the new 3.5 and 3.8 jobs, I removed explicit selection of the
  Debian version underlying the circleci Debian image we run the tests
  under. I could just have easily switched these to "buster", the new
  latest Debian, but I think it's probably better to just go with
  CircleCI's defaults rather than having to remember to check and update
  this every year or so.

o Moved jstests to run against 3.8, since I'm planning to retire testing
  against 3.7 soon per the above. I tried doing this with Cypress as
  well, but ran against diffs due to font differences, so I fell back.

[mypy] First phase of work on testing Python type annotations. (#1079)

o Introduces lib/mypy.ini with a starter set of strictness options.
o All changes required to make these options pass.
o scripts/mypy created to control running mypy based on suggestion at
  https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/existing_code.html#continuous-integration.
o scripts/mypy --report emits a "coverage" report, with a summary % at
  the bottom detailing what % of our non-empty/comment source lines have
  full type information. Currently at 19.92%, probably based largely on
  assignments from literals.
o 'scripts/mypy --report' is hooked into CircleCI under the python-3.8
  job. lib/mypy.ini makes it enforce 3.5-compatible syntax, so I see no
  reason not to run it under our latest Python version only.
o In CircleCI, I modified generation of ~/protobuf.md5 that's used for
  cache key generation to also include vary if our protoc or
  protoc-gen-mypy binaries change, as otherwise we'd currently think the
  prior cache was valid without producing .pyi files.

commit_message:
Retire python-3.7.4 CircleCI project. (#1086)

We'll retain testing only against our oldest (3.5) and newest (3.8)
supported Python versions going forward.

FWIW, the "cypress" test continues to be based on a 3.7.4 image because
efforts to upgrade under https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/pull/1053
failed due to font rendering differences with screenshots. Handling this
upgrade, when needed, will be performed separately, but should not block
removal of running the whole Python suite against 3.7.4.

* check all params as numbers.Integer (not just int)

* be more accepting of int types in JSNumber

Pass --skip-lock to pipenv under pipenv-install Makefile target. (#1093)

By not passing this, we were violating the "doesn't update the
Pipfile.lock." comment on this Makefile target. I don't see where the
lockfile was later used, and so was most likely providing little
benefit.

Finally, invocation before this change took ~1m13s on my machine when
Pipfile.lock wasn't present, and ~33s when it was. With this change,
it's reliably ~17s.

The big question is if the lockfile was providing any value that I
missed picking up, so that's the major review question.

This is a prelude commit to incoming FileUploader-related changes.

### Motivation

Each `ReportSession` has a unique ID, but the server doesn't currently have a good way to _retrieve_ a `ReportSession` by its ID. Instead, the Server currently maintains a dictionary that maps WebsocketHandlers -> ReportSessions.

This patch essentially just changes that dictionary to be a mapping of SessionID -> ReportSession, which will enable other HTTP endpoints to refer to running `ReportSession`s by ID. The upcoming FileUploader HTTP endpoint will use this to add an uploaded file to its associated ReportSession.

### Details

- `ReportSession.id` is now a str instead of an int. (This isn't strictly necessary, but it simplifies some things, and also allows us to easily make report session ID unguessable in the future - if this is a concern - by using a UUID.)
- `Server._session_infos` is now `Server._session_info_by_id`, and stores a mapping of string ID to `SessionInfo`.
- `SessionInfo` now holds its associated WebsocketHandler in addition to the ReportSession.
- Tests are updated, and there's a bit more rigor in the logic for opening and closing new ReportSessions.

This includes many small changes to make mypy understand why various
constructs are safe, and in a few cases to fix real bugs. Many of mypy's
resolved complaints had to do with functions that sometimes return None
(e.g., inspect.currentframe()), and immediate dereferences of these
"union" types made of the expected return type and None.

While making these changes, Python 2-isms were in some cases removed if
they made fixing the problematic statements simpler to fix or the
resulting code easier to understand.

This also introduces scripts/flake8 to allow a minor monkeypatch of
pyflakes (part of flake8) to incorporate
https://github.com/PyCQA/pyflakes/commit/fa92556ca04214fbe292b3d007b34059e8490b5e,
allowing for "# type: ignore[attr-defined]" comments allowing for
specific ignore of Mypy complaints. With this, fixes *all* flake8
complaints in our codebase.

This was committed to pyflakes in August but there have been no releases
and we shouldn't be holding our breath for one per issues like
https://github.com/PyCQA/pyflakes/issues/475.

Store Mapbox token remotely (#948)

- Streamlit's Mapbox API token is no longer hardcoded in `config.py`
- Instead, it's now in a JSON file at https://data.streamlit.io/tokens.json
- A `MapboxToken` utility class on the frontend exposes access to this token:

HTTP file uploader (#1122)

Overhauls the FileUploader widget to send files over HTTP rather than the WebSocket.

(It *looks* like this PR adds lots of code, but I think that's mostly because of formatting changes, and also because it adds more complete test coverage and documentation than the original implementation had. It's roughly the same "code weight" as the original implementation.)

## Server bits

- Adds a new endpoint, `/upload_file`, that's handled by `UploadFileRequestHandler`.
- in addition to widgetID and file data, `/upload_file` requests contain the sessionID of the browser that's doing the uploading.
- The server has a singleton `UploadedFileManager` object. The `/upload_file` endpoint adds files to it. The Server object subscribes to an `UploadedFileManager.on_file_added` event, and it asks the appropriate ReportSession to re-run when that session gets a new uploaded file.
- When a ReportSession is closed, it tells the `UploadedFileManager` to remove all files that belonged to that session (all other sessions' files will remain untouched).
- The server no longer sends "upload progress" event updates back to the client.
- `ReportSession.id` is now a random UUID, so that it's not guessable.

## Frontend bits

- The frontend gets a simple `FileUploadClient` class that just handles assembling `/upload_file` requests. Under the hood it uses axios, which has nice facilities for observing upload progress (which we don't currently use), and cancelling in-progress uploads (which we *do* use).
- The `FileUploader` widget's logic is simplified; it no longer needs to read files before sending them off in the request, it doesn't need to listen to "progress" events from the server, and it fixes some logic errors in the original implementation.

Closes #980

file_uploader: support for multiple files (#1183)

This adds basic support for uploading multiple files to a single st.file_uploader

- `st.file_uploader` now has a new flag, `accept_multiple_files`. It defaults to false.
- When `accept_multiple_files` is true, the frontend widget will accept multiple files, and the Python API will return a list of BytesIO/StringIO objects if 1 or more files are uploaded to the widget. (That is, even if the user uploads a single file, the multi-file uploader will always return a list. The single-file variant will never return a list.)
- `UploadedFileManager` now stores lists of files by `session_id/widget_id` key, instead of just single files.
- The e2e test validates the entire round trip of both single and multiple file uploads.

Closes #912 (there are additional API changes to make to file_uploader, but we're going to be addressing them in future PRs.)

Fix st.cache (#1208)

This fixes breakage that I introduced in #1152 

Rather than creating the cache as a local variable in the st.cache wrapper, we instead manage all caches in a global `_MemCaches` class. Each cache is keyed off its wrapped function's fully qualified name, and its contents.

There's a new `ScriptRunner` test that makes sure that caches are reused across multiple runs of the same script.

Update vega packages, and do proper view finalization (#1233)

Fixes #755, but I'd love to get @domoritz's opinion if he's available.

I'm looking at this issue now because there have been some reports of long-running Streamlit apps blowing up browser memory:

- https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/issues/1148
- https://discuss.streamlit.io/t/animation-to-show-only-the-last-n-datapoints/1686/9

In @domoritz's original bug, he suggested that we were using `view.finalize()` incorrectly, though in the version of `vega-embed` we were previously on, there was no separate `finalize` returned from `embed`. Regardless, I've updated vega, vega-lite, and vega-embed to their latest, and we're now using that finalizer. 

This PR also performs finalization at `componentWillUnmount` time, which is consistent with what `react-vega` does: https://github.com/vega/react-vega/blob/778596cb9209d9ee48c43ceac699fcd4ca5ac30a/packages/react-vega/src/VegaEmbed.tsx#L89

Configuring ReadtheDocs (#1435)

Adds minimal configuration needed to build on ReadtheDocs hosted. No changes were made to existing `make` process, as these files are still part of the development phase.

Fix mypy in CircleCI (#1519)

Our `mypy` task has been failing in CircleCI.

The issue is that `pipenv` is failing to deterministically resolve dependency versions, and is frequently resolving our `tornado=>=5.0, <6.0` dependency to Tornado 6 (because of other transitive dependencies on Tornado).

The solution is to use the `--sequential` flag in our `pipenv install` build step. From the pipenv docs:

> Installation is intended to be as deterministic as possible  use the --sequential flag to increase this, if experiencing issues.

So: pipenv installation is intended to be as deterministic as possible, but it's also possible to "increase its determinism" with a flag! (I think this is...madness.)

This PR *also* cleans up and documents a few things that I found confusing while tracking this down (with @jrhone's help!):

- The `mypy` cache is now stored in the project directory (and gitignored), rather than in `/tmp`
- We expire our CircleCI virtualenv cache key every day; I documented why we do this.
- Added docs to the "Create virtualenv" CircleCI build step.
- Removed the protobuf-caching step from the CircleCI jobs, because it's not actually doing anything.
- Updated the mypy ini to target Python 3.8, and fixed a new mypy warning.

Fixes #463

From a lines-of-code perspective, this is a trivial change; Tornado supports WebSocket compression out of the box, and this PR just flips the switch to enable it.

(This obviously adds a bit of memory and CPU overhead to each WebSocket connection.)

* Ooops resource classs change should have be to the "cypress" flow

* Fix mypy in CircleCI (#1519)

Our `mypy` task has been failing in CircleCI.

The issue is that `pipenv` is failing to deterministically resolve dependency versions, and is frequently resolving our `tornado=>=5.0, <6.0` dependency to Tornado 6 (because of other transitive dependencies on Tornado).

The solution is to use the `--sequential` flag in our `pipenv install` build step. From the pipenv docs:

> Installation is intended to be as deterministic as possible  use the --sequential flag to increase this, if experiencing issues.

So: pipenv installation is intended to be as deterministic as possible, but it's also possible to "increase its determinism" with a flag! (I think this is...madness.)

This PR *also* cleans up and documents a few things that I found confusing while tracking this down (with @jrhone's help!):

- The `mypy` cache is now stored in the project directory (and gitignored), rather than in `/tmp`
- We expire our CircleCI virtualenv cache key every day; I documented why we do this.
- Added docs to the "Create virtualenv" CircleCI build step.
- Removed the protobuf-caching step from the CircleCI jobs, because it's not actually doing anything.
- Updated the mypy ini to target Python 3.8, and fixed a new mypy warning.

1. It shouldn't read environment variables. This happens automatically.

3. Environment variables and the config system are already tested, so no
   need to make sure it also works in the case of STREAMLIT_SERVER_COOKIE_SECRET.

The eslint version we require is part of react-scripts, so we don't need an exact dependency on it. (Removing the explicit eslint dependency makes for easier upgrading of react-scripts.)

Most of the changes in this PR are to fix eslint errors and warnings that this new version of eslint catches.

Fix st.write exception handling (#1682)

If an exception is thrown within `st.write`, pass the correct arguments to `st.exception`.

In our unit tests, we _were_ testing that `st.exception` was called in this circumstance, but we weren't actually validating that it was being called with sane arguments, which was leading to broken tracebacks in user code.

Update DateInput to handle dates below 100 (#1747)

Update DateInput to handle min/max dates below 100

The Date constructor makes assumptions based on the input string that are
inconsistent. When the year is set to below 100, it assumes the year is a
suffix of 19 or 20. (e.g. '0099' returns 1999 year and '0001' returns 2001
year).

This change avoids it by using moment to parse a specific syntax (YYYY/MM/DD)

"streamlit-component-lib" NPM package (#1928)

Contains the new "streamlit-component-lib" npm package as a top-level directory in Streamlit.

- New code lives inside `streamlit/component-lib`. It's its own frontend project, separate from `streamlit/frontend`. It contains all the Streamlit Component bootstrap code that each component needs to use. 
- This code used to be duplicated in each project in the https://github.com/streamlit/component-template repo. This PR is essentially a big de-duplication. (There's a corresponding PR in the template repo here: https://github.com/streamlit/component-template/pull/5)
- The code will eventually get its own set of unit tests - but currently, components (and this new `streamlit-component-lib`) are thoroughly tested via our e2e test script, which runs tests against our component templates - and those templates now use this lib.
- Short instructions on how to publish updates to the npm package are in the README.md.
- The only _new_ stuff in this PR is the packaging bits and READMEs - see `component-lib/package.json` and `component-lib/tsconfig.json`.

### Annoying Apache Arrow wrinkle

There is an annoying wrinkle! `apache-arrow`, the library we use for frontend dataframe handling, has some TypeScript type declaration errors in a few places. This is a known bug (tracked here: https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/ARROW-8394). It's not clear to me why we didn't hit this issue when including the arrow library in our `create-react-app` component templates, but I think it may have to do with dead-code elimination. Or maybe the Babel TypeScript compiler that `create-react-app` uses doesn't have this issue? (This repo deliberately skips Babel, and just uses `tsc` directly, which makes for a much simpler packaging process.)
 
The workaround is to copy the entire set of `apache-arrow` TypeScript declarations -- all its `*.d.ts` files -- into our own declarations override directory, and modify the problematic ones to signal to TypeScript to ignore them for the purposes of typechecking. This is documented in [`component-lib/declarations/README.md`](https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/compare/develop...tconkling:tim/ComponentNPM?expand=1#diff-354cd2595a63e8a5c389f46af76ee495), and when Arrow is fixed, we can back these changes out.

So for the purposes of PR review, just skip all the (many) files inside `declarations/apache-arrow`.

Components: support for bytes (#1981)

Adds support for sending bytes to, and receiving bytes from, components

**Python -> Frontend**:
- In Python, Component functions can now take `bytes` and `bytearray` values as arguments.
- These are delivered to the frontend in the `special_args` list inside `ComponentInstance.proto`. (DataFrames are also sent inside this list.)
- The frontend delivers these bytes args to the iframe as `UInt8Array` values (which is their "native" datatype within protobuf-js).

**Frontend -> Python**:
- The `Streamlit.setComponentValue` function (implemented in our component-lib npm package) can now take `ArrayBuffer` values, and any TypedArray value (`UInt8Array`, `UInt16Array`, etc etc). These are all converted to `UInt8Array` and shipped over to Python, where they're deserialized as `bytes`.

There's also a fix to `WidgetStateManager` in here: `WidgetStateManager.getOrCreateWidgetStateProto` is now just `createWidgetStateProto`, and it always overwrites any existing value. Previously, changing the type of a WidgetState's oneOf value would *not* remove its previous value. In the case of `bytesValue`, its `value` string was also not properly updated.

(It's not clear to me whether this is a bug in protobufjs - it seems like a setter function should be responsible for updating things appropriately? But no such setter function is called in these circumstances - it's just raw data being set.)

WidgetStateManager: don't return `Long` for int values (#2104)

Our "intValue" and "intArrayValue" widget protobuf values represent values with sint64, because sint32 is too small to represent the full range of JavaScript int values. 

Protobufjs uses `number | Long` to represent sint64. However, we're never putting Longs *into* int and intArrays - because none of our widgets use Longs - so we'll never get a Long back out.

This changes the return value of `getIntValue` and `getIntArrayValue` to `number`, and asserts that a `Long` is never returned.

There's also a couple simple tests that verify we can pass MIN_SAFE_INT and MAX_SAFE_INT to these functions.

- "Stale node" pruning

Simplified delta_path representation (#2276)

Removes the "BlockPath" protobuf, and simplifies the representation of "delta paths" in the app.

Previously, the location of a delta was determined with three pieces of data:
- `ForwardMsgMetadata.block_path.container`
- `ForwardMsgMetadata.block_path.path`
- `ForwardMsgMetadata.delta_id`

These are all just different parts of what's now called "delta_path", which is a list of ints that specifies the location of a Delta in the report data tree. That location is now entirely specified via `ForwardMsgMetadata.delta_path`.

(I think this is actually a reduction in code - there are more lines added in this PR, but that's because of additional docstrings and other clarifying comments.)

- (python): `Cursor` now contains the Container it lives in, which means it can also implement `Cursor.delta_path`, which is a property that computes the delta path the cursor points to.
- (python): `DeltaGenerator._get_coordinates` is now called `DeltaGenerator._get_delta_path_str` and is simplified to just use the delta_path. This is a function that's used to generate unique keys for MediaFileManager media.
- (frontend)`ReportRoot` is simplified - it contains a single root `BlockNode` rather than having to maintain two separate `BlockNode` containers for main/sidebar
